ted the brutal bushfires among \\\"new challenges\\\" facing Australia's economy.</p><p>The IMF has again trimmed its outlook for GDP growth this year and next, blaming the revisions on slower growth in emerging markets like India.</p><p>The IMF says global growth will accelerate from 2.9 per cent in 2019 to 3.3 per cent in 2020 and 3.4 per cent next year – that's a reduction of 0.1 percentage point for 2019 and 2020, and a 0.2 per cent cut for 2021 from its predictions in October.</p><p><strong>Read the full story <a href=\\\"https://www.afr.com/world/north-america/imf-sees-global-downturn-bottoming-out-20200120-p53sy7\\\" target=\\\"_blank\\\">here.</a></strong></p>\",\"authorNames\":\"Jacob Greber\",\"relatedAssets\":[],\"relatedImages\":[],\"assetType\":\"LIVE_POST\",\"extendedAbstract\":\"The International Monetary Fund says the global economy's 2019 trade-war induced slowdown may be coming to an end, even as it cited the brutal bushfires among \\\"new challenges\\\" facing Australia's economy.The IMF has again trimmed its outlook for GDP growth this year and next, blaming the revisions on slower growth in emerging markets like India.The IMF says global growth will accelerate from 2.9 per cent in 2019 to 3.3 per cent in 2020 and 3.4 per cent next year – that's a reduction of 0.1 percentage point for 2019 and 2020, and a 0.2 per cent cut for 2021 from\",\"timeStamp\":1579554948000},{\"id\":1030592761,\"categories\":[],\"authors\":[],\"lastModified\":1579554939288,\"sponsored\":false,\"headline\":\"ASX futures inch higher; Australian dollar flat\",\"body\":\"<p>ASX futures up 6 points or 0.1 per cent to 7032 near 7.45am AEDT</p><p>Read <a href=\\\"https://www.afr.com/markets/equity-markets/asx-poised-for-a-flat-open-bhp-ahead-20200121-p53t62\\\" target=\\\"_blank\\\">Before the bell</a></p>\",\"authorNames\":\"Timothy Moore\",\"relatedAssets\":[],\"relatedImages\":[],\"assetType\":\"LIVE_POST\",\"extendedAbstract\":\"ASX futures up 6 points or 0.1 per cent to 7032 near 7.45am AEDTRead Before the bell\",\"timeStamp\":1579554923000},{\"id\":1030592781,\"categories\":[],\"authors\":[],\"lastModified\":1579560835070,\"sponsored\":false,\"headline\":\"Capital Economics sceptical Fed asset buys driving US stock gains\",\"body\":\"<p>Capital Economics is \\\"sceptical\\\" that the Fed's balance sheet expansion late last year played a part in stunning US equity market gains.</p><p>While acknowledging that the two events occurred at around the same time, the economists said they are struggling to see a \\\"portfolio rebalancing\\\" effect after the Fed asset purchases. </p><p>\\\"Instead, the main causes of the upturn in the stock market since October have probably been signs of economic recovery at home after a temporary slowdown during much of 2019, as well as recent progress in trade talks with China,\\\" the economists argued.</p>\",\"authorNames\":\"\",\"relatedAssets\":[],\"relatedImages\":[{\"id\":1030553105,\"categories\":[],\"brands\":[],\"authors\":[],\"url\":\"https://www.fairfaxstatic.com.au/content/dam/images/h/1/k/b/v/5/image.related.articleLeadwide.1500x844.h1l6h9.png/1579560835070.jpg\",\"lastModified\":1576094784525,\"sponsored\":false,\"description\":\"Fed chairman Jerome Powell.\",\"photographer\":\"Bloomberg\",\"type\":\"articleLeadWide\",\"width\":1500,\"height\":844,\"assetType\":\"IMAGE\",\"xLarge@2x\":\"\",\"xLarge\":\"\",\"large@2x\":\"\",\"large\":\"\",\"thumbnail@2x\":\"\",\"thumbnail\":\"\",\"timeStamp\":1576094784525}],\"assetType\":\"LIVE_POST\",\"extendedAbstract\":\"Capital Economics is \\\"sceptical\\\" that the Fed's balance sheet expansion late last year played a part in stunning US equity market gains.While acknowledging that the two events occurred at around the same time, the economists said they are struggling to see a \\\"portfolio rebalancing\\\" effect after the Fed asset purchases. \\\"Instead, the main causes of the upturn in the stock market since October have probably been signs of economic recovery at home after a temporary slowdown during much of 2019, as well as recent progress in trade talks with China,\\\" the economists argued.\",\"timeStamp\":1579555915000},{\"id\":1030592788,\"categories\":[],\"authors\":[],\"lastModified\":1579560742039,\"sponsored\":false,\"headline\":\"ASX bluechips most expensive in the world, says JPMorgan\",\"body\":\"<p>As investors try to reconcile the huge year-to-date rise in Australian shares with the mixed earnings outlook, new research by JP Morgan reveals the local sharemarket is the most expensive in the world if the financial and materials sectors are excluded.</p><p>The analysis, which is based on a one-year forward price-to-earnings measure, shows that the S&P/ASX ASX 200 Index excluding financials and materials is trading at a 37.9 per cent premium to the global developed markets index.</p><p>The extreme valuation is largely attributed to relatively expensive health care and technology stocks, but strategists acknowledge <a href=\\\"https://www.afr.com/link/follow-20180101-p53r9s\\\" target=\\\"_blank\\\">blue chip industrial companies</a> are at generational highs too.</p><p>Read more <a href=\\\"https://www.afr.com/markets/equity-markets/dangerous-path-as-low-rates-push-asx-to-7000-20200116-p53s29\\\" target=\\\"_blank\\\">here.</a></p>\",\"authorNames\":\"Luke Housego\",\"relatedAssets\":[],\"relatedImages\":[{\"id\":1030416020,\"categories\":[],\"brands\":[],\"authors\":[],\"url\":\"https://www.fairfaxstatic.com.au/content/dam/images/h/1/h/e/3/8/image.related.articleLeadwide.1500x844.h1l6hg.png/1579560742039.jpg\",\"lastModified\":1566574924294,\"sponsored\":false,\"description\":\"Aussie stocks are looking expensive.\",\"photographer\":\" Tamara Voninski\",\"type\":\"articleLeadWide\",\"width\":1500,\"height\":844,\"assetType\":\"IMAGE\",\"xLarge@2x\":\"\",\"xLarge\":\"\",\"large@2x\":\"\",\"large\":\"\",\"thumbnail@2x\":\"\",\"thumbnail\":\"\",\"timeStamp\":1566540493221}],\"assetType\":\"LIVE_POST\",\"extendedAbstract\":\"As investors try to reconcile the huge year-to-date rise in Australian shares with the mixed earnings outlook, new research by JP Morgan reveals the local sharemarket is the most expensive in the world if the financial and materials sectors are excluded.The analysis, which is based on a one-year forward price-to-earnings measure, shows that the S&P/ASX ASX 200 Index excluding financials and materials is trading at a 37.9 per cent premium to the global developed markets index.The extreme valuation is largely attributed to relatively expensive health care and technology stocks, but strategists acknowledge blue chip industrial companies are at\",\"timeStamp\":1579556712000},{\"id\":1030592789,\"categories\":[],\"authors\":[],\"lastModified\":1579560538247,\"sponsored\":false,\"headline\":\"BHP delivers 'solid' December quarter report\",\"body\":\"<p>BHP says costs at its giant Escondida copper mine are tracking lower than expected, while output from its petroleum unit will be at the lower end of 2020 guidance.</p><p>The miner reported a 1 per cent quarter-on-quarter fall in iron ore production of 60 million tonnes in the December quarter, though production rose 2 per cent year-on-year in the December half to 121 million tonnes.</p><p>The numbers suggest BHP may just meet the lower end of its full year production target of between 242 million tonnes and 253 million tonnes.</p><p>BHP reported a 6 per cent quarter-on-quarter increase in copper production, while output from Escondida - the world's largest copper mine based in Chile- rose 5 per cent quarter-on-quarter.</p><p>The company said unit costs at Escondida are tracking below full year guidance as a result of higher by-product credits.</p><p>However, BHP warned production from its petroleum unit would be at the lower end of its 2020 guidance of between 110 million-116 million barrels of oil equivalent. </p><p>Petroleum output fell 4 per cent quarter-on-quarter to 28 million barrels of oil equivalent. </p><p>BHP shares are up 24 per cent over the past year.</p>\",\"authorNames\":\"Robert Guy\",\"relatedAssets\":[],\"relatedImages\":[{\"id\":1030489829,\"categories\":[],\"brands\":[],\"authors\":[],\"url\":\"https://www.fairfaxstatic.com.au/content/dam/images/h/1/i/z/1/h/image.related.articleLeadwide.1500x844.h1l6hh.png/1579560538247.jpg\",\"lastModified\":1571411729294,\"sponsored\":false,\"description\":\"The Escondida mine in Chile.\",\"photographer\":\"Bloomberg\",\"type\":\"articleLeadWide\",\"width\":1500,\"height\":844,\"assetType\":\"IMAGE\",\"xLarge@2x\":\"\",\"xLarge\":\"\",\"large@2x\":\"\",\"large\":\"\",\"thumbnail@2x\":\"\",\"thumbnail\":\"\",\"timeStamp\":1571411729178}],\"assetType\":\"LIVE_POST\",\"extendedAbstract\":\"BHP says costs at its giant Escondida copper mine are tracking lower than expected, while output from its petroleum unit will be at the lower end of 2020 guidance.The miner reported a 1 per cent quarter-on-quarter fall in iron ore production of 60 million tonnes in the December quarter, though production rose 2 per cent year-on-year in the December half to 121 million tonnes.The numbers suggest BHP may just meet the lower end of its full year production target of between 242 million tonnes and 253 million tonnes.BHP reported a 6 per cent quarter-on-quarter increase in copper production, while output\",\"timeStamp\":1579556351000},{\"id\":1030592792,\"categories\":[],\"authors\":[],\"lastModified\":1579557171901,\"sponsored\":false,\"headline\":\"Splitit names CEO Brad Paterson as managing director\",\"body\":\"<p>Splitit said that its chief executive officer Brad Paterson has been appointed managing director of the company and a member of its board. </p><p>Jan Koelble has been appointed to the board as an independent non-executive director. </p><p>Co-founder Gil Don and non-executive director Michael DeFranco has resigned from board to pursue new opportunities. The changes are effective immediately.</p>\",\"authorNames\":\"Sarah Turner\",\"relatedAssets\":[],\"relatedImages\":[],\"assetType\":\"LIVE_POST\",\"extendedAbstract\":\"Splitit said that its chief executive officer Brad Paterson has been appointed managing director of the company and a member of its board. Jan Koelble has been appointed to the board as an independent non-executive director. Co-founder Gil Don and non-executive director Michael DeFranco has resigned from board to pursue new opportunities. The changes are effective immediately.\",\"timeStamp\":1579557165000},{\"id\":1030592799,\"categories\":[],\"authors\":[],\"lastModified\":1579557917670,\"sponsored\":false,\"headline\":\"Data#3 expects to meet top end of guidance\",\"body\":\"<p>Information technology company Data#3 expects to hit the top end of its guidance for net profit before tax of between 11 million to 12.5 million in the six months to  December 31. </p><p>For the prior corresponding period it reported a net profit before tax of  million.</p><p>The company will hand in its final audited interim results on February 19.</p><p>Data#3 shares have rallied 149 per cent over the past 12 months. </p>\",\"authorNames\":\"Tom Richardson\",\"relatedAssets\":[],\"relatedImages\":[],\"assetType\":\"LIVE_POST\",\"extendedAbstract\":\"Information technology company Data#3 expects to hit the top end of its guidance for net profit before tax of between 1 million to 2.5 million in the six months to  December 31. For the prior corresponding period it reported a net profit before tax of  million.The company will hand in its final audited interim results on February 19.Data#3 shares have rallied 149 per cent over the past 12 months. \",\"timeStamp\":1579557903000},{\"id\":1030592801,\"categories\":[],\"authors\":[],\"lastModified\":1579565910891,\"sponsored\":false,\"headline\":\"HUB24 hits monthly inflows of 20m\",\"body\":\"<p>Financial services platform operator HUB24 reported net inflows for the quarter ended December of 1.225 billion.</p><p>The result delivered inflows of 2.497 billion for the half year and takes the monthly net inflow run rate to 420 million. In 2019 monthly inflows were 64 million (excluding large one-off transitions).</p><p>The company says it has maintained its position as the platform provider with the highest annualised growth and increased its market share in the first half of the 2020 financial year by 30 basis points to 1.6 per cent.</p><p>HUB24 shares are down 8 per cent over the last 12 months but are 12.7 times higher over the last 5 years. The stock last closed at 1.91.</p>\",\"authorNames\":\"Luke Housego\",\"relatedAssets\":[],\"relatedImages\":[{\"id\":1016865569,\"categories\":[],\"brands\":[],\"authors\":[],\"url\":\"https://www.fairfaxstatic.com.au/content/dam/images/g/t/e/y/h/t/image.related.articleLeadwide.1500x844.h1l6ht.png/1579565910891.jpg\",\"lastModified\":1546913083730,\"sponsored\":false,\"description\":\"Hub24 managing director Andrew Alcock.\",\"photographer\":\"Louie Douvis\",\"type\":\"articleLeadWide\",\"width\":1500,\"height\":844,\"assetType\":\"IMAGE\",\"xLarge@2x\":\"\",\"xLarge\":\"\",\"large@2x\":\"\",\"large\":\"\",\"thumbnail@2x\":\"\",\"thumbnail\":\"\",\"timeStamp\":1546913083730}],\"assetType\":\"LIVE_POST\",\"extendedAbstract\":\"Financial services platform operator HUB24 reported net inflows for the quarter ended December of .225 billion.The result delivered inflows of .497 billion for the half year and takes the monthly net inflow run rate to 20 million. In 2019 monthly inflows were 64 million (excluding large one-off transitions).The company says it has maintained its position as the platform provider with the highest annualised growth and increased its market share in the first half of the 2020 financial year by 30 basis points to 1.6 per cent.HUB24 shares are down 8 per cent over the last 12 months but are 12.7\",\"timeStamp\":1579558655000},{\"id\":1030592807,\"categories\":[],\"authors\":[],\"lastModified\":1579560449187,\"sponsored\":false,\"headline\":\"Resolute, Renergen in trading halts ahead of capital raisings\",\"body\":\"<p>Gold miner Resolute Mining and helium play Renergen have been placed in trading halts ahead of capital raisings. </p><p>Resolute was last week a subject of a <a href=\\\"https://www.afr.com/street-talk/resolute-mining-closes-in-on-gold-mine-sale-20200113-p53r49\\\" target=\\\"_blank\\\">Street Talk item</a> suggesting the company was looking to sell its Ravenswood mine to private equity firm EMR Capital.</p><p>The company <a href=\\\"https://www.asx.com.au/asxpdf/20200114/pdf/44d7t35rj6g5p0.pdf\\\" target=\\\"_blank\\\">confirmed negotiations</a> for a 00 million deal. </p><p>South African focused helium play Renergen has also been placed in a trading halt. </p><p>The stock rallied 80 per cent from its November lows to its highs in December after intersecting helium during a drilling campaign. </p><p>The company released <a href=\\\"https://www.asx.com.au/asxpdf/20200121/pdf/44ddns61vv3p21.pdf\\\" target=\\\"_blank\\\">an update on its Virginia project</a> this morning saying it had intersected more helium. </p>\",\"authorNames\":\"Robert Guy\",\"relatedAssets\":[],\"relatedImages\":[],\"assetType\":\"LIVE_POST\",\"extendedAbstract\":\"Gold miner Resolute Mining and helium play Renergen have been placed in trading halts ahead of capital raisings. Resolute was last week a subject of a Street Talk item suggesting the company was looking to sell its Ravenswood mine to private equity firm EMR Capital.The company confirmed negotiations for a 00 million deal. South African focused helium play Renergen has also been placed in a trading halt. The stock rallied 80 per cent from its November lows to its highs in December after intersecting helium during a drilling campaign. The company released an update on its Virginia project\",\"timeStamp\":1579559610000},{\"id\":1030592813,\"categories\":[],\"authors\":[],\"lastModified\":1579563098092,\"sponsored\":false,\"headline\":\"IAG veteran Ben Bessell set to leave\",\"body\":\"<p>IAG says group executive Ben Bessell is set to leave by the end of March. </p><p>Mr Bessell, who has been providing support to the company's commercial insurance business, had previously been executive general manager of business distribution.</p><p>Prior to this he was CEO of the insurer's Australian business division. </p><p>IAG shares are up 6 per cent over the past year. </p>\",\"authorNames\":\"Robert Guy\",\"relatedAssets\":[],\"relatedImages\":[],\"assetType\":\"LIVE_POST\",\"extendedAbstract\":\"IAG says group executive Ben Bessell is set to leave by the end of March. Mr Bessell, who has been providing support to the company's commercial insurance business, had previously been executive general manager of business distribution.Prior to this he was CEO of the insurer's Australian business division. IAG shares are up 6 per cent over the past year. \",\"timeStamp\":1579560416000},{\"id\":1030592877,\"categories\":[],\"authors\":[],\"lastModified\":1579561884806,\"sponsored\":false,\"headline\":\"Pact taps Citi to sell contract manufacturing division\",\"body\":\"<p>The Raphael Geminder-backed Pact Group is set to unwind years of acquisitions by placing its contract manufacturing division up for sale. </p><p>Citi has been appointed to lead the sale of the business that reported sales of 72 million and earnings before interes, tax, depreciation and amortisation of 5 million in the 2019 financial year. </p><p>Pact acquired Jalco in 2015 for 0 million, paid 0 million for Australian Pharmaceutical Manufacturers in 2016, and acquired Pascoe's in 2017 for 1 million.</p><p>All three deals were struck at an EBITDA multiple of 6.5 times.  </p><p>Pact CEO Sanjay Dayal said the sale would simplify the portfolio and help drive improved returns in the remaining business.</p><p>The sale will also strengthen the company's balance sheet. Gearing increased to three times in the 2019 financial year, up from 2.5 times in the prior year. </p><p>Pact shares have slumped 30 per cent over the past year. The stock was removed from the S&P/ASX200 Index in September last year. </p>\",\"authorNames\":\"Robert Guy\",\"relatedAssets\":[],\"relatedImages\":[{\"id\":1029436979,\"categories\":[],\"brands\":[],\"authors\":[],\"url\":\"https://www.fairfaxstatic.com.au/content/dam/images/h/0/w/e/n/n/image.related.afrArticleInline.620x0.h1l6jx.png/1579561884806.jpg\",\"lastModified\":1519173302982,\"sponsored\":false,\"description\":\"Pact Group chairman Raphael Geminder.\",\"photographer\":\"Pat Scala\",\"type\":\"afrArticleInline\",\"width\":620,\"height\":0,\"assetType\":\"IMAGE\",\"timeStamp\":1519173302982},{\"id\":1029436979,\"categories\":[],\"brands\":[],\"authors\":[],\"url\":\"https://www.fairfaxstatic.com.au/content/dam/images/h/0/w/e/n/n/image.related.articleLeadNarrow.706x0.h1l6jx.png/1579561884806.jpg\",\"lastModified\":1519173302982,\"sponsored\":false,\"description\":\"Pact Group chairman Raphael Geminder.\",\"photographer\":\"Pat Scala\",\"type\":\"articleLeadNarrow\",\"width\":706,\"height\":0,\"assetType\":\"IMAGE\",\"xLarge@2x\":\"\",\"xLarge\":\"\",\"large@2x\":\"\",\"large\":\"\",\"timeStamp\":1519173302982}],\"assetType\":\"LIVE_POST\",\"extendedAbstract\":\"The Raphael Geminder-backed Pact Group is set to unwind years of acquisitions by placing its contract manufacturing division up for sale. Citi has been appointed to lead the sale of the business that reported sales of 72 million and earnings before interes, tax, depreciation and amortisation of 5 million in the 2019 financial year. Pact acquired Jalco in 2015 for 0 million, paid 0 million for Australian Pharmaceutical Manufacturers in 2016, and acquired Pascoe's in 2017 for 1 million.All three deals were struck at an EBITDA multiple of 6.5 times.  Pact CEO Sanjay Dayal said the sale would simplify the portfolio and help\",\"timeStamp\":1579561669000},{\"id\":1030592885,\"categories\":[],\"authors\":[],\"lastModified\":1579563830278,\"sponsored\":false,\"headline\":\"ASX record run snapped as stocks inch lower\",\"body\":\"<p>The record breaking run for Australian stocks could be at an end as the market moves modestly lower in early trade. </p><p>The benchmark S&P/ASX200 Index  is down 14 points to 7065, with a public holiday in the US on Monday meaning there was no directional lead from Wall Street.</p><p>The market had rallied 6 per cent this year ahead of today's trading. </p><p>Leading the market lower is BHP with a decline of 0.75 per cent following the release of its <a href=\\\"https://www.afr.com/companies/mining/bhp-misses-iron-ore-expectations-20200120-p53t2b\\\" target=\\\"_blank\\\">December quarter production report</a>. </p><p>Commonwealth Bank has dropped 0.3 per cent and Transurban is 0.6 per cent lower. </p><p>Woolworths is an early blue chip gainer with an advance of 1 per cent.</p><p>Other notable risers include Sims (up 2.6 per cent), Nearmap (up 2.1 per cent) and Elders, which has gained 1.8 per cent. </p><p>Pilbara Minerals is leading the decliners with a loss of 3.2 per cent.</p>\",\"authorNames\":\"Robert Guy\",\"relatedAssets\":[],\"relatedImages\":[{\"id\":1030393497,\"categories\":[],\"brands\":[],\"authors\":[],\"url\":\"https://www.fairfaxstatic.com.au/content/dam/images/h/1/g/w/p/l/image.related.articleLeadwide.1500x844.h1l6k5.png/1579563830278.jpg\",\"lastModified\":1565156037720,\"sponsored\":false,\"description\":\"Woolworths is among the few blue chip gainers. \",\"photographer\":\"Patrick Scala \",\"type\":\"articleLeadWide\",\"width\":1500,\"height\":844,\"assetType\":\"IMAGE\",\"xLarge@2x\":\"\",\"xLarge\":\"\",\"large@2x\":\"\",\"large\":\"\",\"thumbnail@2x\":\"\",\"thumbnail\":\"\",\"timeStamp\":1565156037387}],\"assetType\":\"LIVE_POST\",\"extendedAbstract\":\"The record breaking run for Australian stocks could be at an end as the market moves modestly lower in early trade. The benchmark S&P/ASX200 Index  is down 14 points to 7065, with a public holiday in the US on Monday meaning there was no directional lead from Wall Street.The market had rallied 6 per cent this year ahead of today's trading. Leading the market lower is BHP with a decline of 0.75 per cent following the release of its December quarter production report. Commonwealth Bank has dropped 0.3 per cent and Transurban is 0.6 per cent lower. Woolworths is an early blue\",\"timeStamp\":1579562450000},{\"id\":1030592943,\"categories\":[],\"authors\":[],\"lastModified\":1579564690641,\"sponsored\":false,\"headline\":\"Dexus: UBS upgrades to \\\"buy\\\"\",\"body\":\"<p>Dexus Property Group has been upgraded to \\\"buy\\\" by UBS as it expects earnings upgrades, strong asset growth and increases in its development pipeline. </p><p>While the broker expects Sydney and Melbourne office rental growth to moderate to between 1 per cent and 3 per cent in 2020-2021, it sees ongoing compression in cap rates, strong cash flows from annual rent escalations and positive leasing spreads. </p><p>UBS also says the quality of the portfolio has been improved through acquisitions and divestments. </p><p>The broker expects Dexus' net tangible asset per share to be 1.60 by June 2020, which implies the market is only attributing 90¢ (or roughly  billion) for the funds management business with .2 billion of third party assets under management, a trading businerss and development/concept pipeline of .7 billion. </p><p>UBS lifted its rating to \\\"buy\\\" from \\\"neutral\\\" on the 3.8 billion group and raised its price target to 3.60 a share from 2.90 a share. </p><p>Dexus, which last traded at 2.58 a share, is up 13 per cent over the past year. </p></p>\",\"authorNames\":\"Robert Guy\",\"relatedAssets\":[],\"relatedImages\":[{\"id\":1030562323,\"categories\":[],\"brands\":[],\"authors\":[],\"url\":\"https://www.fairfaxstatic.com.au/content/dam/images/h/1/k/i/z/7/image.related.articleLeadwide.1500x844.h1l6lr.png/1579564690641.jpg\",\"lastModified\":1576717134764,\"sponsored\":false,\"description\":\"Waterfront Brisbane, a .1 billion Dexus project proposed for the site of Eagle Street Pier by the Brisbane River.\",\"photographer\":\"Queensland state government\",\"type\":\"articleLeadWide\",\"width\":1500,\"height\":844,\"assetType\":\"IMAGE\",\"xLarge@2x\":\"\",\"xLarge\":\"\",\"large@2x\":\"\",\"large\":\"\",\"thumbnail@2x\":\"\",\"thumbnail\":\"\",\"timeStamp\":1576717134764}],\"assetType\":\"LIVE_POST\",\"extendedAbstract\":\"Dexus Property Group has been upgraded to \\\"buy\\\" by UBS as it expects earnings upgrades, strong asset growth and increases in its development pipeline. While the broker expects Sydney and Melbourne office rental growth to moderate to between 1 per cent and 3 per cent in 2020-2021, it sees ongoing compression in cap rates, strong cash flows from annual rent escalations and positive leasing spreads. UBS also says the quality of the portfolio has been improved through acquisitions and divestments. The broker expects Dexus' net tangible asset per share to be 1.60 by June 2020, which implies the market is only attributing 90¢\",\"timeStamp\":1579564668000},{\"id\":1030592970,\"categories\":[],\"authors\":[],\"lastModified\":1579569319964,\"sponsored\":false,\"headline\":\"Home buying intentions hit record high\",\"body\":\"<p>The Commonwealth Bank's latest household spending index shows home buying intentions are running at a record rate indicating the rebound in house prices is likely to continue and help fire up consumption.</p><p>After property values surged by 4 per cent over the past three months – the fastest quarterly growth in a decade - there are also some tentative signs that a positive wealth effect could re-emerge.</p><p>\\\"There are some early signs of a ‘wealth effect’ from the housing market supporting<a href=\\\"https://www.afr.com/policy/economy/house-price-bounce-could-see-better-times-ahead-for-car-sales-20200106-p53p6q\\\" target=\\\"_blank\\\"> spending on motor vehicles</a>, albeit from a very low level, as well as travel and entertainment,” CBA chief economist Michael Blythe said.</p><p><strong>Read the full story <a href=\\\"https://www.afr.com/policy/economy/home-buying-intentions-hit-record-high-20200121-p53t8m\\\" target=\\\"_blank\\\">here</a>.</strong></p>\",\"authorNames\":\"Matthew Cranston\",\"relatedAssets\":[],\"relatedImages\":[],\"assetType\":\"LIVE_POST\",\"extendedAbstract\":\"The Commonwealth Bank's latest household spending index shows home buying intentions are running at a record rate indicating the rebound in house prices is likely to continue and help fire up consumption.After property values surged by 4 per cent over the past three months – the fastest quarterly growth in a decade - there are also some tentative signs that a positive wealth effect could re-emerge.\\\"There are some early signs of a ‘wealth effect’ from the housing market supporting spending on motor vehicles, albeit from a very low level, as well as travel and entertainment,” CBA chief economist\",\"timeStamp\":1579565768000},{\"id\":1030593005,\"categories\":[],\"authors\":[],\"lastModified\":1579566712556,\"sponsored\":false,\"headline\":\"Resolute's 96m raising removes balance sheet concerns says RBC Capital Markets\",\"body\":\"<p>Resolute Mining's <a href=\\\"https://www.asx.com.au/asxpdf/20200121/pdf/44ddr74g1yjx25.pdf\\\" target=\\\"_blank\\\">96 million raising</a> has removed \\\"some\\\" balance sheet concerns RBC Capital Markets analyst Paul Hissey has about the gold miner.</p><p>Resolute is selling new shares at .10 a share - a 6.4 per cent discount to the last closing price - to pay back the Toro Gold bridge facility provided by Taurus Funds Management. </p><p>The miner is raising 46 million through an institutional placement, 5 million through a placement to largest shareholder ICM and a share purchase plan to raise up to 5 million. </p><p>\\\"Given RSG’s cash position (A24.6m), high debt levels (A61m), and required refinancing at the end of the December quarter, this announced equity raise should alleviate some of the cash flow concerns of some investors\\\" Mr Hissey wrote. </p><p>\\\"We remain constructive on Syama as an asset and this announced raise could remove some of the balance sheet concerns we have for the company (compared to domestic peers).\\\"</p></p></p>\",\"authorNames\":\"Robert Guy\",\"relatedAssets\":[],\"relatedImages\":[{\"id\":1030392082,\"categories\":[],\"brands\":[],\"authors\":[],\"url\":\"https://www.fairfaxstatic.com.au/content/dam/images/h/1/g/v/m/a/image.related.afrArticleInline.620x0.h1l6nh.png/1579566712556.jpg\",\"lastModified\":1565068473889,\"sponsored\":false,\"description\":\"Resolute Mining CEO John Welborn.\",\"photographer\":\"Billy-Ray Stokes\",\"type\":\"afrArticleInline\",\"width\":620,\"height\":0,\"assetType\":\"IMAGE\",\"timeStamp\":1565068473889},{\"id\":1030392082,\"categories\":[],\"brands\":[],\"authors\":[],\"url\":\"https://www.fairfaxstatic.com.au/content/dam/images/h/1/g/v/m/a/image.related.articleLeadNarrow.706x0.h1l6nh.png/1579566712556.jpg\",\"lastModified\":1565068473889,\"sponsored\":false,\"description\":\"Resolute Mining CEO John Welborn.\",\"photographer\":\"Billy-Ray Stokes\",\"type\":\"articleLeadNarrow\",\"width\":706,\"height\":0,\"assetType\":\"IMAGE\",\"xLarge@2x\":\"\",\"xLarge\":\"\",\"large@2x\":\"\",\"large\":\"\",\"timeStamp\":1565068473889}],\"assetType\":\"LIVE_POST\",\"extendedAbstract\":\"Resolute Mining's 96 million raising has removed \\\"some\\\" balance sheet concerns RBC Capital Markets analyst Paul Hissey has about the gold miner.Resolute is selling new shares at .10 a share - a 6.4 per cent discount to the last closing price - to pay back the Toro Gold bridge facility provided by Taurus Funds Management. The miner is raising 46 million through an institutional placement, 5 million through a placement to largest shareholder ICM and a share purchase plan to raise up to 5 million. \\\"Given RSG’s cash position (A24.6m), high debt levels (A61m), and required refinancing at the end\",\"timeStamp\":1579566386000},{\"id\":1030593028,\"categories\":[],\"authors\":[],\"lastModified\":1579568592658,\"sponsored\":false,\"headline\":\"AMCIL says further gains for stocks \\\"to be more challenging\\\"\",\"body\":\"<p>Listed investment company AMCIL has cautioned that stocks may struggle to keep rallying given the reliance on multiple expansion rather than earnings growth. </p><p>The wariness came as the 80 million LIC delivered a half year profit of .8 million, up slightly from .7 million at the same time last year. </p><p>AMCIL's portfolio produced a six month return of 10.2 per cent, beating the S&P/ASX200 Accumulation Index that gained 3.8 per cent over the same time. </p><p>The 12-month return was 29.2 per cent, again beating the S&P/ASX200 Accumulation Index's 25.4 per cent advance. </p><p>The strong performance was attributed to the \\\"healthy exposure\\\" of the portfolio to blue chips like CSL (the biggest position in its portfolio with an 8.9 per cent weighting), Macquarie Group, James Hardie and Wesfarmers. </p><p>Smaller companies that performed well included Carsales.com, Objective Corp and Xero. </p><p>\\\"With the Australian equity market trading at high levels, driven more by the expansion of valuation mutliple rather than earnings growth, further significant growth in the market is likely to be more challenging.\\\"</p></p>\",\"authorNames\":\"Robert Guy\",\"relatedAssets\":[],\"relatedImages\":[{\"id\":1030403160,\"categories\":[],\"brands\":[],\"authors\":[],\"url\":\"https://www.fairfaxstatic.com.au/content/dam/images/h/1/h/4/6/0/image.related.articleLeadwide.1500x844.h1l6o4.png/1579568592658.jpg\",\"lastModified\":1567155143559,\"sponsored\":false,\"description\":\"CSL CEO Paul Perreault\",\"photographer\":\"David Rowe\",\"type\":\"articleLeadWide\",\"width\":1500,\"height\":844,\"assetType\":\"IMAGE\",\"xLarge@2x\":\"\",\"xLarge\":\"\",\"large@2x\":\"\",\"large\":\"\",\"thumbnail@2x\":\"\",\"thumbnail\":\"\",\"timeStamp\":1567155143559}],\"assetType\":\"LIVE_POST\",\"extendedAbstract\":\"Listed investment company AMCIL has cautioned that stocks may struggle to keep rallying given the reliance on multiple expansion rather than earnings growth. The wariness came as the 80 million LIC delivered a half year profit of .8 million, up slightly from .7 million at the same time last year. AMCIL's portfolio produced a six month return of 10.2 per cent, beating the S&P/ASX200 Accumulation Index that gained 3.8 per cent over the same time. The 12-month return was 29.2 per cent, again beating the S&P/ASX200 Accumulation Index's 25.4 per cent advance. The strong performance was attributed to the \\\"healthy exposure\\\" of the portfolio\",\"timeStamp\":1579567456000},{\"id\":1030593107,\"categories\":[],\"authors\":[],\"lastModified\":1579569247221,\"sponsored\":false,\"headline\":\"Why Mike Henry is about to hit the accelerator at BHP\",\"body\":\"<p>The best thing about Mike Henry’s first set of numbers as BHP chief executive is that there’s nothing crashed, burnt or broken.</p><p>In recent years, the December half has become a bit of a disaster zone for <a href=\\\"https://www.afr.com/company/bhp-99\\\" target=\\\"_blank\\\">BHP</a>.</p><p>In the six months ended December 2018, for example, there was<a href=\\\"https://www.afr.com/link/follow-20180101-h1canj\\\" target=\\\"_blank\\\"> the infamous train derailment in Western Australia</a>, a fire at its Spence copper mine in Chile and a breakdown in the acid plant at Olympic Dam. </p><p>In the second half of 2017, there was a fire in the Pilbara and a series of problems caused by wet weather across its coal mines. And two years prior, BHP was rocked by the <a href=\\\"https://www.afr.com/link/follow-20180101-p52isq\\\" target=\\\"_blank\\\">tragic dam collapse at its Samarco iron ore mine in Brazil</a>.</p><p>But this year, BHP’s quarterly report for December – which doubles as an early look at the miner’s numbers for the six months to December 31 – paints a picture of calm.</p><p><strong>Find Chanticleer's full analysis of BHP's quarterly production report <a href=\\\"https://www.afr.com/chanticleer/why-mike-henry-is-about-to-hit-the-accelerator-at-bhp-20200121-p53ta8\\\" target=\\\"_blank\\\">here</a>.</strong> </p>\",\"authorNames\":\"James Thomson\",\"relatedAssets\":[],\"relatedImages\":[{\"id\":1030521293,\"categories\":[],\"brands\":[],\"authors\":[],\"url\":\"https://www.fairfaxstatic.com.au/content/dam/images/h/1/j/n/b/h/image.related.articleLeadwide.1500x844.h1l6qb.png/1579569247221.jpg\",\"lastModified\":1575015685629,\"sponsored\":false,\"description\":\"Mike Henry plans to accelerate BHP's leaner-is-better strategy.\",\"photographer\":\"David Rowe\",\"type\":\"articleLeadWide\",\"width\":1500,\"height\":844,\"assetType\":\"IMAGE\",\"xLarge@2x\":\"\",\"xLarge\":\"\",\"large@2x\":\"\",\"large\":\"\",\"thumbnail@2x\":\"\",\"thumbnail\":\"\",\"timeStamp\":1575015685629}],\"assetType\":\"LIVE_POST\",\"extendedAbstract\":\"The best thing about Mike Henry’s first set of numbers as BHP chief executive is that there’s nothing crashed, burnt or broken.In recent years, the December half has become a bit of a disaster zone for BHP.In the six months ended December 2018, for example, there was the infamous train derailment in Western Australia, a fire at its Spence copper mine in Chile and a breakdown in the acid plant at Olympic Dam. In the second half of 2017, there was a fire in the Pilbara and a series of problems caused by wet weather across its\",\"timeStamp\":1579569185000},{\"id\":1030593153,\"categories\":[],\"authors\":[],\"lastModified\":1579569898122,\"sponsored\":false,\"headline\":\"Western Areas signs up BHP, Jinchuan\",\"body\":\"<p>Western Areas has signed new offtake agreements with BHP and China's Jinchuan for nickel concentrate from the miner's Forrestania operations. </p><p>BHP's Nickel West has signed a three year agreement from February for the purchase of 10,000 tonnes a year with a 30,000 tonne a year limit. </p><p>Jinchuan has signed a two year contract from February 1 and will buy 10,000 tonnes a year with a 20,000 tonne a year limit. </p><p>Western Areas shares are up 28 per cent over the past year, with the price of nickel boosted last year by Indonesia's bringing forward of a ban on nickel ore exports. </p>\",\"authorNames\":\"Robert Guy\",\"relatedAssets\":[],\"relatedImages\":[],\"assetType\":\"LIVE_POST\",\"extendedAbstract\":\"Western Areas has signed new offtake agreements with BHP and China's Jinchuan for nickel concentrate from the miner's Forrestania operations. BHP's Nickel West has signed a three year agreement from February for the purchase of 10,000 tonnes a year with a 30,000 tonne a year limit. Jinchuan has signed a two year contract from February 1 and will buy 10,000 tonnes a year with a 20,000 tonne a year limit. Western Areas shares are up 28 per cent over the past year, with the price of nickel boosted last year by Indonesia's bringing forward of a ban on nickel ore exports. \",\"timeStamp\":1579569789000},{\"id\":1030593164,\"categories\":[],\"authors\":[],\"lastModified\":1579570520163,\"sponsored\":false,\"headline\":\"Look beyond the hype on ethical investing\",\"body\":\"<p>Many Australians are reflecting on investment portfolios, given the confronting fires and other environmental considerations.</p><p>A big swing towards <a href=\\\"https://www.afr.com/wealth/personal-finance/why-it-pays-to-go-green-20200109-p53q2x\\\" target=\\\"_blank\\\">protecting a portfolio</a> from the repercussions of the ravages of changing climatic conditions as well as skewing the investments towards companies that may offer solutions is well underway.</p><p>This month <a href=\\\"https://www.afr.com/companies/financial-services/blackrock-dumps-thermal-coal-20200114-p53rd0\\\" target=\\\"_blank\\\">BlackRock</a> has made much of \\\"putting sustainability at the centre of how it invests\\\", joining an ever-crowded space of fund managers that proclaim they will change the way they consider their options.</p><p>The dilemma for investors is that marketing can overtake reality.</p><p><strong>Read the full analysis <a href=\\\"https://www.afr.com/wealth/personal-finance/look-beyond-the-hype-on-ethical-investing-20200120-p53syl\\\" target=\\\"_blank\\\">here</a>. </strong></p>\",\"authorNames\":\"Giselle Roux\",\"relatedAssets\":[],\"relatedImages\":[],\"assetType\":\"LIVE_POST\",\"extendedAbstract\":\"Many Australians are reflecting on investment portfolios, given the confronting fires and other environmental considerations.A big swing towards protecting a portfolio from the repercussions of the ravages of changing climatic conditions as well as skewing the investments towards companies that may offer solutions is well underway.This month BlackRock has made much of \\\"putting sustainability at the centre of how it invests\\\", joining an ever-crowded space of fund managers that proclaim they will change the way they consider their options.The dilemma for investors is that marketing can overtake reality.Read the full analysis here. \",\"timeStamp\":1579570414000},{\"id\":1030593256,\"categories\":[],\"authors\":[],\"lastModified\":1579573468965,\"sponsored\":false,\"headline\":\"Hedge funds sound note of caution on global equity markets\",\"body\":\"<p>It's not often that you get not one, but two, of the most highly regarded and successful investment managers urging investors to beware the ongoing stampede in global equity markets.</p><p>But as asset prices across the board – equities, properties, low-grade corporate debt –have continued their surge, top executives from the world's biggest hedge fund, Bridgewater Associates, and from leading alternative asset management firm Oaktree Capital have both sounded a note of caution.</p><p>Bridgewater's co-chief investment officer, Greg Jensen, who helps manage some US160 billion (32 billion) in assets, gave a good explanation for the ferocity of the global share market rally in an interview with the <em>Financial Times </em>last week.</p><p>\\\"There will no longer be an attempt by any of the developed world's major central banks to normalise interest rates,\\\" he said. \\\"That's a big deal.\\\"</p><p>He added that Bridgewater was \\\"more cautious\\\" on US stocks which were seen as \\\"frothy\\\".</p><p><a href=\\\"https://www.afr.com/markets/debt-markets/howard-marks-on-why-the-markets-are-right-20191121-p53crd\\\" target=\\\"_blank\\\">Howard Marks, the co-founder of Oaktree Capital,</a> which manages more than US120 billion, was even blunter. When he was asked last week in an interview on Bloomberg Television whether now was a good time to be investing, he replied: \\\"It is not.\\\"</p><p>Read the full story <a href=\\\"https://www.afr.com/companies/financial-services/does-the-fed-s-mandate-include-bailing-out-risky-hedge-funds-20200120-p53swx\\\" target=\\\"_blank\\\">here</a></p>\",\"authorNames\":\"Karen Maley\",\"relatedAssets\":[],\"relatedImages\":[],\"assetType\":\"LIVE_POST\",\"extendedAbstract\":\"It's not often that you get not one, but two, of the most highly regarded and successful investment managers urging investors to beware the ongoing stampede in global equity markets.But as asset prices across the board – equities, properties, low-grade corporate debt –have continued their surge, top executives from the world's biggest hedge fund, Bridgewater Associates, and from leading alternative asset management firm Oaktree Capital have both sounded a note of caution.Bridgewater's co-chief investment officer, Greg Jensen, who helps manage some US160 billion (32 billion) in assets, gave a good explanation for the ferocity of the global share market rally\",\"timeStamp\":1579573453000},{\"id\":1030593331,\"categories\":[],\"authors\":[],\"lastModified\":1579575920893,\"sponsored\":false,\"headline\":\"Capital Economics sees mining sector's share of GDP declining\",\"body\":\"<p>Capital Economics believes that the mining sector's importance in Australia is set to decline.</p><p>\\\"Mining investment has slumped and a structural slowdown is underway in China’s economy,\\\" the economists said. </p><p>The economists said that, by 2030, mining’s share of GDP could hit 7.5 per cent, from a current level of 9.4 per cent.</p>\",\"authorNames\":\"Sarah Turner\",\"relatedAssets\":[],\"relatedImages\":[],\"assetType\":\"LIVE_POST\",\"extendedAbstract\":\"Capital Economics believes that the mining sector's importance in Australia is set to decline.\\\"Mining investment has slumped and a structural slowdown is underway in China’s economy,\\\" the economists said. The economists said that, by 2030, mining’s share of GDP could hit 7.5 per cent, from a current level of 9.4 per cent.\",\"timeStamp\":1579575907000},{\"id\":1030593383,\"categories\":[],\"authors\":[],\"lastModified\":1579577291225,\"sponsored\":false,\"headline\":\"Morgan Stanley sees downside risk to bank sector earnings\",\"body\":\"<p>Morgan Stanley noted that average total shareholder return for the major banks lagged the ASX 200 index by 14 per cent in 2019. </p><p>\\\"We believe the end of the super cycle and an ongoing earnings per share and return on equity downgrade cycle are driving under performance,\\\" Morgan Stanley's bank analysts team led by Richard Wiles said.</p><p>Operating conditions have become more challenging and and the regulatory environment more uncertain, the analysts added. </p><p>\\\"We believe banks will under-perform again in 2020 if they remain in an EPS downgrade cycle.\\\"</p><p>But they suggested there could be \\\"swing factors\\\" for the sector in 2020 that could determine the path of the sector's performance. </p><p>These include a rebound in mortgage growth, loan and deposit repricing, ongoing pressure on banking fees, an easing on compliance and reinvestment burdens and accelerating cost reductions. </p><p>\\\"On balance, we still see downside risk to our FY20E and FY21E EPS estimates,\\\" they said.</p>\",\"authorNames\":\"Sarah Turner\",\"relatedAssets\":[],\"relatedImages\":[],\"assetType\":\"LIVE_POST\",\"extendedAbstract\":\"Morgan Stanley noted that average total shareholder return for the major banks lagged the ASX 200 index by 14 per cent in 2019. \\\"We believe the end of the super cycle and an ongoing earnings per share and return on equity downgrade cycle are driving under performance,\\\" Morgan Stanley's bank analysts team led by Richard Wiles said.Operating conditions have become more challenging and and the regulatory environment more uncertain, the analysts added. \\\"We believe banks will under-perform again in 2020 if they remain in an EPS downgrade cycle.\\\"But they suggested there could be \\\"swing factors\\\" for the sector in 2020 that could\",\"timeStamp\":1579577281000},{\"id\":1030593386,\"categories\":[],\"authors\":[],\"lastModified\":1579577406274,\"sponsored\":false,\"headline\":\"Kip McGrath considering strategic options\",\"body\":\"<p>Online education and specialist child tuition business Kip McGrath has told investors it's in preliminary discussions over a number of strategic approaches made to the business.</p><p>Its hand was forced after a speeding ticket from the ASX asking why its shares had climbed 16 per cent in the last week despite there being no official news out of the company.</p><p>The education business also informed the ASX two recent broker reports had assigned buy recommendations on the shares above current prices.</p><p>For financial year 2019 it posted EBITDA of .2 million on revenue of 6.3 million.</p>\",\"authorNames\":\"Tom Richardson\",\"relatedAssets\":[],\"relatedImages\":[],\"assetType\":\"LIVE_POST\",\"extendedAbstract\":\"Online education and specialist child tuition business Kip McGrath has told investors it's in preliminary discussions over a number of strategic approaches made to the business.Its hand was forced after a speeding ticket from the ASX asking why its shares had climbed 16 per cent in the last week despite there being no official news out of the company.The education business also informed the ASX two recent broker reports had assigned buy recommendations on the shares above current prices.For financial year 2019 it posted EBITDA of .2 million on revenue of 6.3 million.\",\"timeStamp\":1579577374000},{\"id\":1030593395,\"categories\":[],\"authors\":[],\"lastModified\":1579579634968,\"sponsored\":false,\"headline\":\"Bank of Japan keeps policy steady in January by 7-2 vote\",\"body\":\"<p>The Bank of Japan kept monetary policy steady and nudged up its economic growth forecasts on Tuesday, as the government's spending package and receding pessimism over the global outlook take some pressure off the central bank to top up stimulus. </p><p>As widely expected, the BOJ maintained its short-term interest rate target at negative 0.1 per cent and pledged to guide 10-year government bond yields to around 0 per cent, by a 7-2 vote.</p><p>It also maintained guidance that commits it to keeping rates at current low levels, or even cut them, until risks keeping it from achieving its 2 per cent inflation goal subside.</p><p>In a quarterly review of its forecasts, the BOJ revised up its growth projection for the fiscal year beginning in April to 0.9 per cent from an estimate of 0.7 per cent growth made in October, helped by a boost from the government's fiscal stimulus package.</p><p>BOJ Governor Haruhiko Kuroda will hold a news conference this afternoon.</p>\",\"authorNames\":\"Reuters\",\"relatedAssets\":[],\"relatedImages\":[{\"id\":1030016876,\"categories\":[],\"brands\":[],\"authors\":[],\"url\":\"https://www.fairfaxstatic.com.au/content/dam/images/h/1/8/u/3/w/image.related.articleLeadwide.1500x844.h1l6yb.png/1579579634968.jpg\",\"lastModified\":1544080795948,\"sponsored\":false,\"description\":\"Haruhiko Kuroda, governor of the Bank of Japan.\",\"photographer\":\" \",\"type\":\"articleLeadWide\",\"width\":1500,\"height\":844,\"assetType\":\"IMAGE\",\"xLarge@2x\":\"\",\"xLarge\":\"\",\"large@2x\":\"\",\"large\":\"\",\"thumbnail@2x\":\"\",\"thumbnail\":\"\",\"timeStamp\":1544080795948}],\"assetType\":\"LIVE_POST\",\"extendedAbstract\":\"The Bank of Japan kept monetary policy steady and nudged up its economic growth forecasts on Tuesday, as the government's spending package and receding pessimism over the global outlook take some pressure off the central bank to top up stimulus. As widely expected, the BOJ maintained its short-term interest rate target at negative 0.1 per cent and pledged to guide 10-year government bond yields to around 0 per cent, by a 7-2 vote.It also maintained guidance that commits it to keeping rates at current low levels, or even cut them, until risks keeping it from achieving its 2 per cent inflation\",\"timeStamp\":1579577591000},{\"id\":1030593538,\"categories\":[],\"authors\":[],\"lastModified\":1579580528462,\"sponsored\":false,\"headline\":\"Asia sags as virus concerns mount \",\"body\":\"<p>Asian shares sagged on Tuesday, with investors shying away from stocks as concerns about a deadly new virus mounted.</p><p>\\\"The coronavirus crisis occurring in the central Chinese city of Wuhan is a building concern,\\\" said Stephen Innes, Asia Pacific market strategist at AxiCorp.</p><p>\\\"The cost to the global economy can be quite staggering in negative GDP terms if this outbreak reaches epidemic proportions,\\\" he said. </p><p>\\\"If things turn critical, it could provide a massive blow to the airline industry and a knockout punch to local tourism,\\\" the strategist said. </p><p>Hong Kong lost 2.3 per cent, Japan's Nikkei 225 dropped 0.9 per cent and the CSI 300 fell 1.3 per cent on the Chinese mainland.</p><p>Read more <a href=\\\"https://www.afr.com/world/asia/sydney-airport-to-screen-for-deadly-virus-20200121-p53t8w\\\" target=\\\"_blank\\\">here</a></p>\",\"authorNames\":\"Sarah Turner\",\"relatedAssets\":[],\"relatedImages\":[],\"assetType\":\"LIVE_POST\",\"extendedAbstract\":\"Asian shares sagged on Tuesday, with investors shying away from stocks as concerns about a deadly new virus mounted.\\\"The coronavirus crisis occurring in the central Chinese city of Wuhan is a building concern,\\\" said Stephen Innes, Asia Pacific market strategist at AxiCorp.\\\"The cost to the global economy can be quite staggering in negative GDP terms if this outbreak reaches epidemic proportions,\\\" he said. \\\"If things turn critical, it could provide a massive blow to the airline industry and a knockout punch to local tourism,\\\" the strategist said. Hong Kong lost 2.3 per cent, Japan's Nikkei 225 dropped 0.9 per cent and the\",\"timeStamp\":1579580462000},{\"id\":1030593593,\"categories\":[],\"authors\":[],\"lastModified\":1579582495512,\"sponsored\":false,\"headline\":\"Boss Resources eyes restart of uranium production at Honeymoon\",\"body\":\"<p>The chief executive of Boss Resources says the time is right for a proposed re-start of production at the Honeymoon uranium mine in South Australia after six years of laying dormant because uranium demand is rising and more <a href=\\\"https://www.afr.com/companies/energy/the-rolls-royce-option-for-australian-nuclear-power-20190822-p52jpn\\\" target=\\\"_blank\\\">nuclear power stations</a> are likely to be built. </p><p>Duncan Craib said the group has spent about 8 million over the past three years in preparation for a re-start, with a feasibility study released on Tuesday showing a clear and sensible path to production beginning again. </p><p>\\\"We're now in a position of operational readiness,'' Mr Craib says.</p><p>He says while uranium prices currently remain depressed at about US5/lb on the spot market, demand is rising because those low prices meant there were no new mines being constructed around the world.</p><p>Boss Resources also announced on Tuesday that Peter O'Connor would become its new chairman. </p><p>Read more <a href=\\\"https://www.afr.com/companies/mining/boss-resources-eyes-honeymoon-uranium-mine-revival-20200121-p53t9s\\\" target=\\\"_blank\\\">here</a></p>\",\"authorNames\":\"Simon Evans\",\"relatedAssets\":[],\"relatedImages\":[{\"id\":1030593453,\"categories\":[],\"brands\":[],\"authors\":[],\"url\":\"https://www.fairfaxstatic.com.au/content/dam/images/h/1/l/6/z/x/image.related.articleLeadwide.1500x844.h1l73t.png/1579582495512.jpg\",\"lastModified\":1579578914932,\"sponsored\":false,\"description\":\" \",\"photographer\":\"Photo: Glenn Campbell\",\"type\":\"articleLeadWide\",\"width\":1500,\"height\":844,\"assetType\":\"IMAGE\",\"xLarge@2x\":\"\",\"xLarge\":\"\",\"large@2x\":\"\",\"large\":\"\",\"thumbnail@2x\":\"\",\"thumbnail\":\"\",\"timeStamp\":1579578914805}],\"assetType\":\"LIVE_POST\",\"extendedAbstract\":\"The chief executive of Boss Resources says the time is right for a proposed re-start of production at the Honeymoon uranium mine in South Australia after six years of laying dormant because uranium demand is rising and more nuclear power stations are likely to be built. Duncan Craib said the group has spent about 8 million over the past three years in preparation for a re-start, with a feasibility study released on Tuesday showing a clear and sensible path to production beginning again. \\\"We're now in a position of operational readiness,'' Mr Craib says.He says while uranium prices currently remain\",\"timeStamp\":1579582469000},{\"id\":1030593658,\"categories\":[],\"authors\":[],\"lastModified\":1579584287734,\"sponsored\":false,\"headline\":\"ASX snaps record-breaking run as tech, travel sectors weigh \",\"body\":\"<p>The ASX snapped a five-session streak of record-breaking gains on Tuesday, with technology and travel firms notably weak.</p><p>The S&P/ASX 200 index declined 13 points, or 0.2 per cent, at 7066.30.</p><p>In the technology sector, TechnologyOne shares declined 4.7 per cent, WiseTech lost 4 per cent, and nearmap fell 3.1 per cent.</p><p>Travel-related companies were lower as well. Corporate Travel fell 4.6 per cent and Webjet fell 3.5 per cent and Flight Centre fell 3 per cent. Sydney Airport declined 3 per cent and Qantas fell 1.7 per cent.</p><p>Hub24 shares declined 5.3 per cent after updating shareholders on net inflows. </p><p>On the plus side, Woolworths advanced 2 per cent and Coles rose 1.3 per cent, helping the consumer staples sector outperform the rest of the market.</p><p>In the mining sector, Fortescue Metals rose 2.1 per cent and Newcrest advanced 1.2 per cent. </p>\",\"authorNames\":\"Sarah Turner\",\"relatedAssets\":[],\"relatedImages\":[],\"assetType\":\"LIVE_POST\",\"extendedAbstract\":\"The ASX snapped a five-session streak of record-breaking gains on Tuesday, with technology and travel firms notably weak.The S&P/ASX 200 index declined 13 points, or 0.2 per cent, at 7066.30.In the technology sector, TechnologyOne shares declined 4.7 per cent, WiseTech lost 4 per cent, and nearmap fell 3.1 per cent.Travel-related companies were lower as well. Corporate Travel fell 4.6 per cent and Webjet fell 3.5 per cent and Flight Centre fell 3 per cent. Sydney Airport declined 3 per cent and Qantas fell 1.7 per cent.Hub24 shares declined 5.3 per cent after updating shareholders on net inflows. On the plus side, Woolworths\",\"timeStamp\":1579584269000},{\"id\":1030593702,\"categories\":[],\"authors\":[],\"lastModified\":1579585809370,\"sponsored\":false,\"headline\":\"Antipodes directors, manager executives hold more than 8 million shares\",\"body\":\"<p>Antipodes Global Investors said that its directors and directors and executives of its manager held more than 8 million shares in the company as at December 31, after a number of those parties acquired shares in Antipodes Global. </p><p>The aggregate holding equates to a top ten shareholding in the listed investment company, it said.</p>\",\"authorNames\":\"Sarah Turner\",\"relatedAssets\":[],\"relatedImages\":[],\"assetType\":\"LIVE_POST\",\"extendedAbstract\":\"Antipodes Global Investors said